Today was the Day of Silence. Staying silent all day (more or less; well, a little less - I did mess up a couple times "Thanks," "I think I just exposed most of my photo paper," and "Whoa!") was kind of like having a permanent glass bubble around me at all times. Being mute created a dichotomy between the bustling world of Greenhills and I; at times my day was almost surreal. Try as I might to get my meaning across the barrier, sometimes it just wasn't good enough. I gestured, I jumped, I mouthed, I learned 80% of the Greenhills population I come in contact with is completely and totally lost at interpreting charades. The separation was kind of enlightening. When you aren't participating in the world through speech, you give yourself space to further dedicate time to other pasttimes - such as observing society. Being a bystander truly puts things in perspective; and can make it all the harder to join in again, once you understand - or perhaps only think you understand - how you will be received. On the college note, I madly gestured to Mr. T that I would go meet with him tomorrow (who knows if he actually got what I was trying to convey). I am still completely at a loss. Decisions, decisions. I'm not normally very good at making them in a timely fashion; I like to keep my options open until the very last minute. And this is probably the most important decision of my life yet. Usually I try to picture myself in each different decision, and imagine if I would have regrets or not. If I can't even picture myself in the situation, it's obvious it's not the right choice. But now, I see myself at all these colleges. Three different me's: Margaret1, Margaret2, and Margaret3. Margaret1 has grown fond of coffee and can't live without her daily mango smoothie. She practically lives in the WashU Architecture Studio at Givens and catches sleep whenever she can. Her fingers are always covered in some sort of art gunk, whether it be charcoal, glue, sawdust, or blood from cuts. Although the work is fickle and the bristol board never stays where she wants it, she is always satisfied when the finished masterpiece is revealed. Plus there are cute guys in studio in wee hours of the morning. Margaret2 has no time for contacts. She wears glasses and every day is a battle between her (weapons: calculator, pencil, and gigantic eraser) versus the next physics set (danger level: 10.4). She keeps telling herself she really needs to learn that thing called time management, and find time to get to the gym after gaining weight from the delicious Cornell food. Plus she yearns for fun, but is sacrificing some of this in order to be the best she can be and meet her challenges. She works like a dog to satisfy all her interests, but they are, as a result, satiated to the max. Margaret3 is close to home but likes to pretend she isn't. She often visits her apartment friend so that her friend can have something new to eat besides burnt pancakes and overcooked omelettes. She holds poker night at her dorm every week or so; her high school friends have become lifetime friends. Margaret is having trouble deciding which Margaret she wants to become by September of this year.

I was so tired when I came home today, I started to take a nap at around 7 o'clock. When my parents come home later, I sleep a little more and then go up to greet them. As soon as my foot hits the top stair, their psychic xray vision reaches my face and suddenly I am bombarded with demands to TAKE OFF YOUR CONTACTS! I'm not talking stink bombs, either. I'm talking big-time atom bombs that leaves years worth of unstable dangerous radiation in Japan level bombardment. Now I understand that some (dumbass vain) girls in Taiwan were trying to take their contacts off when their eyes were too dry, and ended up scraping off the surface of their eyes. I understand that some of them wore contacts that made their pupils larger in the pursuit of beauty, trading off for oxygen getting to their eye. They lost at least half their eyesight through their lack of foresight. However, I am still indignant when I am practically attacked for someone else's stupidity. It's good to be informed. To know the dangers of the situations. But just because the little black box or big grey paper has a few cautionary things to say doesn't mean that your life thus merits major conflict over eyes that aren't even dry, an alternative spring break that might cause a nail to puncture your skin and give you a disease and make you die, a trip to europe that may end up in you getting on a subway and getting blown to bits. 
I don't want to sound ungrateful here. Which is probably why I am, once again, venting to my livejournal. But urgency can be expressed in other ways, alternative to raising the voice several decibels above humanly possible, pounding blood pressure, and eventual deafness to anything reasonable at all. Urgency also doesn't mean that you forget to say "Hello, how was your day?" It doesn't mean that one party stays mad, madd, and madder upstairs, while the other goes downstairs to drop a couple tears on her bed. 
I'd rather just wear glasses.
The overprotectiveness is touching? I know it shows they care. I know they must have seen it somewhere in the news, and worried about it for an unhealthy amount of time (for my parents anyway), then burst the dam to explode the built up words on - me. Because that's what they do. 
My results are inconclusive. This is how they are, this is how I'm not. That is what it is. By the time I finish this entry I will have accepted it and moved on, perhaps grooving to my newly downloaded "So Fresh and So Clean (Clean);" they will still be upstairs with my unsigned permission slip, emotions coursing through their bodies. Perhaps another half hour later I will make my slow way up the stairs once more, 
and s(m)ooth(e) things over. 
Until then.

Today was bad. Well. To avoid using the word "bad," let me just say it was "not good." Sassurean negation - Randy would be proud, yes?
Since I feel bad venting too much to actual people, I can just spill any stress out to this bright white screen. I have Forensics Districts tomorrow, and I don't feel too confident. I have tons of Chemistry to do, and I don't want to do it. I have photos to take, and I don't have film. I have Chinese to do, and I don't know how to go about doing it. I have a pimple, and I don't care. 
Now for the answers: I'll just practice my gestures to make them more firm for Districts tomorrow. I will do Chemistry. I will borrow my dad's digital camera. I will ask my mom how to do Chinese. I will... pop it.
As for college, everyone around me is building up the anticipation for the big decisions. Sometimes I hope I get in; sometimes I hope I don't so my decision will be easier.
Oh, did I mention I am catching a cold? (God I feel like I'm complaining too much even when no one's suffering these words.) 
I got home and decided to do what I do when I catch a cold in warm weather: wash and wax my car. Somehow it doesn't make me dizzy even when it should. Perhaps it's because I can splash water on my face anytime to get myself back. Anyway, my reasoning is, it makes me feel better - it sweats out the germs. My bedroom's too cold for a disease, anyway. Some sun is good. 
As I was bounding down to my room to retrieve my keys, I jumped down each half flight of stairs. And on the last one, I got too enthusiastic and banged my head on the ceiling beam. Laughing? This is not the first time this has happened. First let me say for the record that I even left a mark on the wood where my head banged it; I also retained a slight bump with minimal bleeding. Which, I just realized, did not prevent me from jumping down the stairs once again two minutes ago. (Although this time, I thankfully did not hit my head.)
The first time was at school, jumping down the stairs to the forum - that time it was against the metal beam, which was... painful. Of course right afterwards I landed as if nothing had happened, and quickly checked the premises as well as I could with the throbbing pain through my head to make sure no one had seen me. Embarrassing.
There must be a ceiling beam magnet embedded in my frontal lobe.
